00:01:08.130 --> 00:01:14.390
COLE: They're shortchanging the engineering
process to meet a schedule.

00:01:14.390 --> 00:01:18.050
WE UNCOVER A WHISTLEBLOWER FIRED AS HE FOUGHT
FOR SAFETY:

00:01:18.050 --> 00:01:23.590
WOODS: There's no doubt there are bad repairs
going out the door on the 787 aircraft.

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:32.220
WE GO BEHIND CLOSED DOORS, ONTO THE FACTORY
FLOOR, TO REVEAL A WORLD BOEING KEEPS SECRET.

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:54.020
UC WORKER VIDEO: I wouldn't fly on one of
these planes…

00:01:54.020 --> 00:02:06.880
Because I see the quality of the fu**ing sh*t
going down

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:08.819
around here.

00:02:08.819 --> 00:02:12.739
TITLE: "BROKEN DREAMS: THE BOEING 787"
JANUARY 16TH, 2013.

00:02:12.739 --> 00:02:15.500
TAKAMATSU, JAPAN - A BRAND-NEW BOEING 787
DREAMLINER MAKES AN EMERGENCY LANDING.

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:22.130
PASSENGERS KNEW THE PLANE WAS IN TROUBLE:
AOYA KAZUNORI/passenger: I looked outside

00:02:22.130 --> 00:02:24.650
and saw white smoke.

00:02:24.650 --> 00:02:27.940
That's when I realised the danger.

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:31.760
KEN'ICHI KAWAMURA/passenger: The burning plastic
smell got worse.

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:34.880
/ I thought we were going to crash.

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:44.960
TAKEUCHI KOJI/Fireman: On closer inspection,
we observed a blue box that had expanded in

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:46.320
size.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:51.349
THE BLUE BOX WAS ONE OF THE DREAMLINER'S TWO
LITHIUM ION BATTERIES –THE MOST POWERFUL

00:02:51.349 --> 00:02:52.960
- AND RISKY - EVER PERMITTED

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:55.010
ON A COMMERCIAL AIRCRAFT.

00:02:55.010 --> 00:02:58.860
Newsreader: It's just the latest in a string
of embarrassments for Boeing's state of the

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:00.580
art aircraft.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:06.470
NINE DAYS EARLIER A DREAMLINER BATTERY HAD
CAUGHT FIRE IN BOSTON, MASSACHUSETTS.

00:03:06.470 --> 00:03:08.770
TWO BATTERY FAILURES IN LESS THAN TWO WEEKS.

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:13.400
NEWS BITE: Japanese carrier All Nippon Airways
and Japan Airlines have grounded their fleets

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:14.850
of Boeing 787

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:15.850
Dreamliners.

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:20.510
JAPAN AIRLINES AND ANA HAD BEEN THE FIRST
TO FLY THE DREAMLINER - NOW THEY BECAME THE

00:03:20.510 --> 00:03:22.430
FIRST TO CANCEL ALL FLIGHTS.

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:24.100
NEWS BITE: Breaking news.

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:25.720
The United States Federal Aviation…

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:31.560
WITHIN 24 HOURS, THE U.S. SAFETY REGULATOR,
THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION, GROUNDED

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:32.560
THE 787.

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:38.530
NEWS BITE: All 50 of the new Boeing 787 Dreamliners
have now been grounded…

00:03:38.530 --> 00:03:40.650
THE REST OF THE WORLD FOLLOWED.

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:43.830
NO BOEING FLEET HAD EVER BEEN FORCED FROM
SERVICE.

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:57.990
BUT ON JANUARY 17, 2013, THE DREAM WAS OVER.

00:03:57.990 --> 00:03:59.880
I'M WILL JORDAN.

00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:03.900
FOR A YEAR, MY TEAM AND I HAVE BEEN INVESTIGATING
THE DREAMLINER.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:06.680
IT'S THE BOEING COMPANY'S BIG BET ON THE FUTURE…

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:12.510
A PLANE CREATED TO SAVE FUEL, IMPROVE COMFORT,
AND BOOST PROFITS.

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:19.560
AND ONE BUILT IN A NEW WAY - DESIGNED AND
MANUFACTURED BY SCORES OF COMPANIES AROUND

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:25.570
THE GLOBE.

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:36.350
THE COMPANY THAT MAKES THE BATTERY IS GS YUASA,
BASED IN KYOTO.

00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:39.270
WE WANTED THEM TO TELL US WHAT HAD GONE SO
WRONG.

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:43.650
SOUND: Security Guard in Japanese.

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:46.270
Will: Al Jazeera.

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:48.900
Guard: Al Jazeera.

00:04:48.900 --> 00:04:52.160
We wonder whether you might be able to do

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.160
an interview?

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:54.160
THEY REFUSED.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:58.880
SPOKESWOMAN: We have a contract with Boeing
so we can't, we can't tell any comments to

00:04:58.880 --> 00:04:59.880
you.

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:04.350
THE BATTERY IS ONLY ONE PART OF THE DREAMLINER'S
COMPLEX ELECTRICAL SYSTEM.

00:05:04.350 --> 00:05:08.910
THERE'S ALSO A CHARGER, MADE AT A FACTORY
THOUSANDS OF KILOMETRES AWAY.

00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:14.120
WHAT HAPPENED THERE, SHOWS BOEING LEARNT YEARS
AGO JUST HOW DANGEROUS A LITHIUM ION BATTERY

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:20.130
COULD BE.

00:05:20.130 --> 00:05:24.960
IN TUCSON, ARIZONA, WE TRACKED DOWN MICHAEL
LEON – AN ELECTRICAL TECHNICIAN.

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:28.710
MICHAEL LEON / Former Securaplane technician:
I've been working electronics since I was

00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:29.720
17 years old, and I joined

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:38.960
the paratroopers and I was assigned to an
electronics battalion of the 82nd airborne.

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:46.330
LEON: this is the first time I've been here
since, since 2007.

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:51.330
It's hard to believe that this is what's left
of a

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:56.639
three story engineering structure.

00:05:56.639 --> 00:06:02.660
ON A NOVEMBER MORNING IN 2006, LEON AND DOZENS
OF OTHER WORKERS CLOCKED IN AT SECURAPLANE

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:04.300
- THE COMPANY THAT MAKES

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:06.290
THE BATTERY CHARGER.

00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:11.430
LEON: I started a pot of coffee then I went
into my lab and started working on my battery

00:06:11.430 --> 00:06:13.350
charging unit.

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:14.600
AND THEN IT HAPPENED.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:21.120
LEON: …and there was a very loud explosion
and all of a sudden I was lying on the floor

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:22.930
and there it was coming out

00:06:22.930 --> 00:06:24.200
the side of this battery.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:27.740
It was about that big, and it wasn't like
fire.

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:30.060
It looked like a jet afterburner, like

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:35.520
jet exhaust.

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:40.320
THE PROTOTYPE BATTERY SECURAPLANE WAS USING
TO TEST ITS CHARGER HAD EXPLODED.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:47.600
KIRK WINES / Former Securaplane technician:
I heard a very loud series of metallic rattling

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:48.600
bangs.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:50.680
A kind of

00:06:50.680 --> 00:06:51.680
shhhhhh.

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:54.300
And just this jet of steam.

00:06:54.300 --> 00:06:59.170
LEON: The fire was literally rolling up the
walls around me and, and on the ceiling, I

00:06:59.170 --> 00:07:00.460
could just see it eating up

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.910
all around me…

00:07:02.910 --> 00:07:09.330
WINES: I know if that had happened on board
an aircraft, there, there would be no chance

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:16.290
of survival.

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:21.110
IT WAS THE BIGGEST CHEMICAL FIRE IN TUCSON'S
HISTORY.

00:07:21.110 --> 00:07:26.479
A TEN THOUSAND SQUARE FOOT, THREE-STOREY STRUCTURE,
BURNT TO THE GROUND.

00:07:26.479 --> 00:07:32.330
RICHARD LUKSO / Securaplane founder: …after
my building burned down, after that they realized

00:07:32.330 --> 00:07:34.070
very emphatically

00:07:34.070 --> 00:07:43.889
the danger of this chemistry.

00:07:43.889 --> 00:07:48.259
RICHARD LUKSO KNOWS WELL THE CHEMISTRY OF
THE DREAMLINER BATTERY.

00:07:48.259 --> 00:07:50.340
BOEING CHOSE THE MOST POWERFUL THERE IS…

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:52.259
BUT ALSO THE MOST VOLATILE.

00:07:52.259 --> 00:07:56.889
LUKSO:
they went to lithium cobalt which is way up

00:07:56.889 --> 00:07:59.249
here as far as danger.

00:07:59.249 --> 00:08:03.240
LUKSO STEPPED DOWN AS SECURAPLANE PRESIDENT
JUST BEFORE THE FIRE.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:08.389
HE STARTED A NEW COMPANY TO MAKE LITHIUM ION
BATTERIES FOR BUSINESS JETS.

00:08:08.389 --> 00:08:13.080
LUKSO WAS A TRUE BELIEVER IN THE TECHNOLOGY.

00:08:13.080 --> 00:08:14.509
THEN HE BEGAN TESTING.

00:08:14.509 --> 00:08:23.919
BULLET TEST VIDEO: Two, 3.3 amp hour series
battery pack bullet test.

00:08:23.919 --> 00:08:32.659
LUKSO WENT BEYOND EVEN THE LATEST INDUSTRY
GUIDELINES - GOING SO FAR AS TO FIRE BULLETS

00:08:32.659 --> 00:08:34.099
INTO BATTERIES, TO SEE IF

00:08:34.099 --> 00:08:36.940
THEY COULD BE MADE SAFE FOR MILITARY APPLICATIONS.

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:40.130
(BATTERY WALK/TALK) LUKSO: Yeah.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:46.269
You could run the test that you feel that
you need to meet the requirements to

00:08:46.269 --> 00:08:53.910
be safe, but you also need to have a conscience
that's going to tell you I want to do the

00:08:53.910 --> 00:08:56.860
extreme."

00:08:56.860 --> 00:09:02.180
IN THE END, TESTING WITH A CONSCIENCE, LUKSO
COULDN'T MAKE THE BATTERIES MEET THE REQUIREMENTS.

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:05.160
HIS NEW COMPANY FAILED.

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:10.110
LUKSO: …we became proficient in destroying
batteries.

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:13.660
And, and the more we learned about it, the
worst it got.

00:09:13.660 --> 00:09:14.660
I

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:16.809
mean, oh, my God, we kept digging and digging.

00:09:16.809 --> 00:09:20.110
We were saying I wonder what the rest of the
guys are doing.

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:21.110
Well,

00:09:21.110 --> 00:09:25.990
I guess we knew.

00:09:25.990 --> 00:09:30.980
BY REST OF THE GUYS HE MEANS BOEING.

00:09:30.980 --> 00:09:33.639
AND THEY WERE TESTING TO A WEAKER STANDARD…

00:09:33.639 --> 00:09:42.370
ONE WRITTEN BY THE FAA SPECIFICALLY FOR THE
DREAMLINER.

00:09:42.370 --> 00:09:45.709
IT'S THE FAA'S JOB TO REGULATE AIR SAFETY.

00:09:45.709 --> 00:09:50.980
BUT WHEN IT COMES TO BUILDING AIRPLANES, THE
FAA DELEGATES OVERSIGHT ALMOST COMPLETELY

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:52.380
TO THE AIRCRAFT

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:54.529
MANUFACTURERS.

00:09:54.529 --> 00:10:00.189
WHEN IT COMES TO THE BATTERY AND BEYOND, BOEING
LARGELY POLICES ITSELF.

00:10:00.189 --> 00:10:02.660
THE BATTERIES PASSED BOEING'S TESTS.

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:07.680
IN LINE WITH THE FAA RULES, BOEING SAID THE
787 BATTERIES WOULD VIRTUALLY NEVER CATCH

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:09.889
FIRE ON BOARD AN AIRCRAFT.

00:10:09.889 --> 00:10:14.550
THEN, THEY FAILED TWICE IN JUST NINE DAYS.

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:18.079
BOEING HAS NOT UNCOVERED THE ROOT CAUSE OF
THE FAILURES.

00:10:18.079 --> 00:10:26.449
IT FOUND A WORK AROUND: A STRONG STEEL CASE,
MORE INSULATION, AND AN EXHAUST FOR NOXIOUS

00:10:26.449 --> 00:10:27.449
FUMES.

00:10:27.449 --> 00:10:31.319
SINNETT: …any fire will be impossible because
there's not enough oxygen to support combustion.

00:10:31.319 --> 00:10:34.389
BUT SEVERAL LEADING SCIENTISTS HAVE THEIR
DOUBTS.

00:10:34.389 --> 00:10:39.329
DONALD SADOWAY / MIT: I don't think it's a
sufficient fix / Even inside that steel box

00:10:39.329 --> 00:10:41.319
with all of its

00:10:41.319 --> 00:10:48.170
fortifications, all of the elements are still
there for fire.

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:53.899
DESPITE NOT KNOWING THE ROOT CAUSE, AMERICA'S
SAFETY REGULATOR, THE FAA, WAS SATISFIED.

00:10:53.899 --> 00:10:59.179
AND IN APRIL 2013, THE DREAMLINER WAS BACK.

00:10:59.179 --> 00:11:02.759
BUT THIS STORY GOES FAR BEYOND A BURNING BATTERY.

00:11:02.759 --> 00:11:05.360
IT BEGINS AT BOEING ITSELF.

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:08.360
"This is it.

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:14.690
The first American commercial jet capable
of economical transatlantic service.

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:17.380
The Boeing 707 jet

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:18.380
clipper.

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:23.800
SINCE ITS CREATION IN SEATTLE NEARLY A CENTURY
AGO, BOEING HAD DEVELOPED A REPUTATION AS

00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:25.670
A WORLD-CLASS ENGINEERING

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:26.950
COMPANY.

00:11:26.950 --> 00:11:32.389
BUT IN 1997 BOEING CHANGED.

00:11:32.389 --> 00:11:37.329
IT MERGED WITH COMPETITOR, MCDONNELL DOUGLAS.

00:11:37.329 --> 00:11:40.810
TWO COMPANIES WITH TWO VERY DIFFERENT BUSINESS
MODELS.

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:48.569
STAN SORSCHER / Former Boeing engineer: the
merger was all about transforming our successful

00:11:48.569 --> 00:11:51.059
culture and business

00:11:51.059 --> 00:11:55.059
model into the same business model that McDonnell
Douglas had used unsuccessfully.

00:11:55.059 --> 00:11:58.629
ABW-002 / 1:05
ABOULAFIA: you basically shortchange engineering,

00:11:58.629 --> 00:12:01.059
you stop doing aggressive new product developments;
you run the

00:12:01.059 --> 00:12:02.920
business for cash.

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:07.699
THE NEW BOEING MOVED ITS HEADQUARTERS FROM
SEATTLE, THE ONLY HOME THE COMPANY HAD EVER

00:12:07.699 --> 00:12:12.249
KNOWN, TO CHICAGO.

00:12:12.249 --> 00:12:22.139
IT BEGAN SLASHING INVESTMENT IN RESEARCH,
IN ORDER TO CUT COSTS AND MAXIMISE WALL STREET

00:12:22.139 --> 00:12:23.139
RETURNS.

00:12:23.139 --> 00:12:28.569
CYNTHIA COLE / Former Boeing engineer: I felt
it was wrong, I felt it was going to take

00:12:28.569 --> 00:12:31.049
the company in the wrong

00:12:31.049 --> 00:12:37.310
direction and I thought that quality would
suffer and the integrity of the product would

00:12:37.310 --> 00:12:38.310
suffer.

00:12:38.310 --> 00:12:47.420
KEVIN SANDERS / Former Boeing manager: I feel
that that legacy and that history and that

00:12:47.420 --> 00:12:49.120
competence has been

00:12:49.120 --> 00:12:54.430
hijacked by a bunch of corporate thugs.

00:12:54.430 --> 00:13:00.959
BY 2003, IT WAS TIME TO LAUNCH A NEW PLANE.

00:13:00.959 --> 00:13:05.930
BUT BOEING'S NEW BOARD WAS RELUCTANT TO INVEST
THE BILLIONS NEEDED.

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:12.819
DOMINIC GATES / Seattle Times: The board made
it clear that they wanted this plane made

00:13:12.819 --> 00:13:14.369
for less money.

00:13:14.369 --> 00:13:15.369
They

00:13:15.369 --> 00:13:21.239
wanted it made for $5 billion and they wanted
partners to come in and pay the rest.

00:13:21.239 --> 00:13:24.660
ABW-002/ 9:35
Richard Aboulafia: It's expensive.

00:13:24.660 --> 00:13:26.432
So how do you make that happen?

00:13:26.432 --> 00:13:28.119
Well, you promise them that you can do it
for

00:13:28.119 --> 00:13:33.199
less / and then worry about the consequences
later.

00:13:33.199 --> 00:13:36.980
BOEING CAME UP WITH A PLAN TO SAVE ITSELF
MONEY.

00:13:36.980 --> 00:13:40.989
IT WOULD PUSH THE COSTS ONTO ITS MAJOR SUPPLIERS.

00:13:40.989 --> 00:13:48.149
BOEING WOULD CALL THEM PARTNERS – AND THEY
WOULD DESIGN AND PAY FOR THE PARTS THEY BUILT.

00:13:48.149 --> 00:13:51.319
BOEING'S JOB WOULD BE TO ASSEMBLE THE PLANE.

00:13:51.319 --> 00:13:58.319
GATES: It was almost as if at times you thought
Boeing executives believed, well, maybe they

00:13:58.319 --> 00:13:59.319
could sit in Chicago

00:13:59.319 --> 00:14:03.179
and have / other companies / do things, and
they would just rake in the money somehow

00:14:03.179 --> 00:14:04.850
by putting it all together

00:14:04.850 --> 00:14:10.209
and putting a Boeing sticker on it at the
end.

00:14:10.209 --> 00:14:25.829
RIGHT ON SCHEDULE, BOEING ROLLED OUT THE DREAMLINER
ON SUNDAY JULY THE 8TH 2007, 7-8-7.

00:14:25.829 --> 00:14:33.290
Tom Brokaw: Airlines with us today have made
a big commitment to Boeing and to this airplane.

00:14:33.290 --> 00:14:34.290
So far they have

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:36.329
ordered 677 of them.

00:14:36.329 --> 00:14:44.260
ABOULAFIA: I think in a lot of ways, July
8, 2007 was one of the more magical moments

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:45.779
I've seen in the industry…

00:14:45.779 --> 00:14:51.279
Brokaw: Watching us live around the world,
broadcasting I'm told in 45 countries in 9

00:14:51.279 --> 00:14:53.689
languages for the premier of

00:14:53.689 --> 00:14:58.339
this very exciting Boeing 787 Dreamliner.

00:14:58.339 --> 00:15:05.980
GATES: We were all inside the factory with
artificial lighting, big stage, Tom Brokaw,

00:15:05.980 --> 00:15:07.290
huge screens…

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:09.519
Then they

00:15:09.519 --> 00:15:13.670
opened the doors of this giant assembly bay…

00:15:13.670 --> 00:15:17.470
ABOULAFIA: And in rolls this beautiful, beautiful
aircraft.

00:15:17.470 --> 00:15:24.240
GATES: And there it is, sitting in the sun
and we all stream outside and we all touch

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:27.899
it and none of us noticed.

00:15:27.899 --> 00:15:28.899
Smile!

00:15:28.899 --> 00:15:33.550
ABOULAFIA: And I'm reassured by the executives
involved that it's going to fly within two

00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:34.550
months.

00:15:34.550 --> 00:15:35.550
One, two, three.

00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:39.410
JON OSTROWER / Wall Street Journal
What I realized walking around it is that

00:15:39.410 --> 00:15:47.309
you could look up in the wheel well and you
could see daylight.

00:15:47.309 --> 00:15:54.769
GATES: We learned that the whole thing was
a sham.

00:15:54.769 --> 00:15:59.709
MIKE BAIR / 787 Program Manager: Beautiful
isn't it?

00:15:59.709 --> 00:16:00.939
Absolutely beautiful…

00:16:00.939 --> 00:16:05.339
GATES: They rolled out this fake airplane.

00:16:05.339 --> 00:16:08.489
OSTROWER: I realized the doors were made of
plywood.

00:16:08.489 --> 00:16:13.779
GATES: This plane that we were admiring was
completely a shell inside

00:16:13.779 --> 00:16:18.829
JAMES MCNERNEY / BOEING CEO: None of this
would be possible, of course, without exceptional

00:16:18.829 --> 00:16:19.829
leadership.

00:16:19.829 --> 00:16:24.759
ABOULAFIA: There's only two conclusions you
can draw: You have executives there who are

00:16:24.759 --> 00:16:26.590
either lying, in which

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:29.519
case they are completely clueless because
they are going to get caught in two months,

00:16:29.519 --> 00:16:30.519
or you have a complete

00:16:30.519 --> 00:16:35.339
disconnect between the people who are working
on the plane, the engineers, and the executives

